Task: Install simple utilities from GitHub source code.

Why install from source:
- Get newest version
- Customize build options
- Learn how software is compiled
- Some tools are not available in apt

Common methods:
1. ./configure → make → make install
2. CMake
3. git clone + make
4. Language-based tools (cargo, python setup.py)

Example 1: bat

bat is an improved version of cat with syntax highlighting.

Install Rust:
curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh
source $HOME/.cargo/env

Clone and build:
git clone https://github.com/sharkdp/bat.git
cd bat
cargo build --release

Install:
sudo cp target/release/bat /usr/local/bin/

Test:
bat --version
bat /etc/hosts

Example 2: htop

htop is an interactive process viewer.

Install dependencies:
sudo apt update
sudo apt install build-essential libncurses5-dev libncursesw5-dev

Download and build:
wget https://github.com/htop-dev/htop/releases/download/3.3.0/htop-3.3.0.tar.xz
tar -xvf htop-3.3.0.tar.xz
cd htop-3.3.0
./configure
make
sudo make install

Test:
htop

Example 3: fzf

fzf is a command line fuzzy finder.

Clone and install:
git clone https://github.com/junegunn/fzf.git
cd fzf
./install

Test:
fzf

Conclusion:
Installing from source usually means:
download → build → install → test
